\begin_layout Section
Sampling 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

-bridges
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this first section, we demonstrate that the exact generalized bridge
 sampler proposed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "chap:4"

\end_inset

 produces samples from the desired target distribution.
 Furthermore, we show that both the approximate and exact samplers are robust
 to the specific conditions imposed on the nature of the stochastic process
 to be bridged in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "chap:2"

\end_inset

.
 We also confirm that the approximate sampler does not formally draw from
 the true generalized bridge distribution, but note that the approximate
 sample paths are still qualitatively similar to exact sample paths.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As usual, we first fix the objects of study.
 Though the theoretical results in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "chap:4"

\end_inset

 characterize a generalized bridge sampler for the specific case of Itô
 diffusions with finite speed measure, we will consider a more general class
 of processes in this section to demonstrate the broad applicability of
 the proposed generalized bridge samplers.
 In particular, we will focus on Lévy processes of the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
dX_{t}=-\lambda\left(X_{t}-\mu\right)dt+\sigma dL_{t},\label{eq:ou-sde}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for some initial condition on 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{0}$
\end_inset

 and Lévy process 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda,\sigma>0$
\end_inset

.
 Solutions to this SDE are known as Lévy-driven Ornstein-Uhlenbeck (OU)
 processes.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is a Wiener process, 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is an Itô diffusion satisfying the assumptions outlined in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "chap:2"

\end_inset

.
 This so-called Gaussian OU process, or OU diffusion, is both theoretically
 interesting (representing the only non-trivial stationary, Gaussian, and
 Markovian process) and practically useful as a model for a wide range of
 processes (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
before "Section 1.2 in"
key "hirsa-2012"

\end_inset

 for applications in finance, for instance).
 In general, we will refer to the parameter vector of such a process as
 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=(\mu,\lambda,\sigma)$
\end_inset

, and the joint law at 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}=\{0,1\}$
\end_inset

 of a solution to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ou-sde"

\end_inset

 with initial condition 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{0}\sim F$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{\theta}(F,L)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In all simulations to be carried out, the relevant process is simulated
 over the time interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

 with step size 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta=1/100$
\end_inset

 using the Euler-Maruyama scheme.
 In this section, we will repeatedly need to sample from 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{\theta}(F,L)$
\end_inset

; this can be easily done by simulating an unconstrained solution to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ou-sde"

\end_inset

 with initial condition 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{0}\sim F$
\end_inset

, and taking its values at 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}=\{0,1\}$
\end_inset

.
 The exact generalized bridge sampler uses 
\begin_inset Formula $M=10$
\end_inset

 (the number of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

-values simulated in order to calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\rho}$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

