\begin_layout Standard
Now, note that an unconstrained solution to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ou-sde"

\end_inset

 with initial condition 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{0}\sim F$
\end_inset

 can be equivalently viewed as its own 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{\theta}(F,L)$
\end_inset

-bridge.
 This insight suggests that we merely need to verify that a 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{\theta}(F,L)$
\end_inset

-bridge of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is equal in distribution to the unconstrained process 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{0}\sim F$
\end_inset

.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "tab:KS-stats"

\end_inset

, we present Kolmogorov-Smirnov (K-S) statistics comparing the marginal
 distribution at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1/2$
\end_inset

 of unconstrained processes to their 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{\theta}(F,L)$
\end_inset

-bridges sampled approximately and exactly.
 The relative running times of the two samplers are also given.
 A significant K-S statistic says that we may reject the null hypothesis
 that the samples being compared are drawn from the same distribution at
 some appropriate confidence level.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition to evaluating the correctness of the proposed generalized bridge
 samplers for a Gaussian OU process with 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=(0,1,1)$
\end_inset

, which satisfies the assumptions of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "chap:2"

\end_inset

, we also test the correctness of the samplers for 
\end_layout

\begin_layout aEnumerate (ClassicThesis)
an OU process driven by a standard 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

-stable Lévy process 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=(0,1,1)$
\end_inset

, which is not an Itô diffusion, and 
\end_layout

\begin_layout aEnumerate (ClassicThesis)
the Wiener process, which does not have finite speed measure.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note the Wiener process is a limiting case of the Gaussian OU process when
 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\rightarrow(0,0,1)$
\end_inset

.
 For each process, we evaluate the quality of the sampled bridges for 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 equal to
\end_layout

\begin_layout aEnumerate (ClassicThesis)
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}(0,1/2)$
\end_inset

, the stationary distribution of a Gaussian OU process with 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=(0,1,1)$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout aEnumerate (ClassicThesis)
\begin_inset Formula $2\mbox{Bern}-1$
\end_inset

, a discrete distribution, and
\end_layout

\begin_layout aEnumerate (ClassicThesis)
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Expo}$
\end_inset

, a distribution with relatively heavy tails (where the log-density decays
 linearly instead of quadratically like the Gaussian distribution).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "tab:KS-stats"

\end_inset

 confirms that for the OU diffusion, we cannot reject the null hypothesis
 that the exact sampler draws from the true distribution at the 
\begin_inset Formula $95\%$
\end_inset

 confidence level for a variety of initial distributions.
 On the other hand, we can reject the null hypothesis for the approximate
 sampler at the same confidence level; this is expected, since 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "thm:approx-sim"

\end_inset

 says explicitly that the approximate sampler for an Itô diffusion draws
 generalized bridges conditional on such bridges being hit by an independent
 hitting diffusion.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We note that the quality of the approximate sampler is inversely correlated
 with the computing time required to sample exact bridges.
 This intuitively highlights a tradeoff between speed and quality, and is
 also formally expected: If the approximate sampler produces low quality
 samples, then their probability of intersection with a hitting diffusion
 is low.
 Since the exact sampler accepts, with high probability, sample paths that
 are less likely to intersect with a hitting diffusion, it must spend more
 time simulating hitting diffusions for any given proposal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The bridges produced by the exact sampler for the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

-stable OU and Wiener processes also appear to be generally of high quality,
 suggesting that the proposed method is fairly robust to the assumptions
 made in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "chap:2"

\end_inset

.
 It is only in the extreme case of an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Expo}$
\end_inset

 initial distribution and an 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

-stable Lévy-driven OU process that the exact sampler fails to draw from
 the true bridge distribution at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1/2$
\end_inset

.
 We conjecture that the infinite variance of the innovations of the process
 and the relatively heavy tail of the initial distribution dramatically
 reduce the probability of intersection with a mean reverting hitting process.
 In particular, our choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $M=10$
\end_inset

 Monte Carlo samples for estimating the hitting probability may result in
 Metropolis-Hastings acceptance ratios that are too coarse to produce exact
 paths in a finite sample scenario.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unexpectedly, both the approximate and exact samplers appear to sample from
 the true bridge distribution when the underlying process is a Wiener process,
 which does not have finite speed measure.
 We do not have a theoretically grounded explanation for this phenomenon;
 however, we see this result as further evidence that the assumptions made
 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "chap:2"

\end_inset

 regarding the sorts of processes that can be bridged may be relaxed in
 future research.
\end_layout

