\begin_layout Standard
While it is true that the approximate sampler does not formally sample from
 the true generalized bridge distribution, we show in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:q-q"

\end_inset

 that the approximate and exact samplers for the Gaussian OU bridges produce
 qualitatively similar samples.
 In general, we see that the approximate samples are slightly thinner-tailed
 than the true distribution: This is expected, since conditional on the
 approximate samples being hit by a hitting process (which in this case
 mean-reverts to 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

), the approximate sample paths should tend toward 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 as well.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:q-q"

\end_inset

 reveals that 
\begin_inset Formula $F\sim\mbox{Expo}$
\end_inset

 results in the lowest quality samples, whether from the approximate or
 exact sampler (corroborating the high K-S statistics observed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "tab:KS-stats"

\end_inset

).
 The values around 
\begin_inset Formula $3.5$
\end_inset

 which deviate substantially from the true distribution can be understood
 as coming from the sample paths which were initialized at extreme values,
 but which have since mean reverted towards 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
 We hypothesize that the exact sampler has difficulty correcting these paths
 because the coarse estimates used for the M-H acceptance ratios cannot
 capture their low probability of intersection with a mean reverting hitting
 process, as described above.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In light of the qualitative similarity of the approximate and exact samplers,
 it is worth noting that the K-S statistics presented in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "tab:KS-stats"

\end_inset

 represent the most liberal estimates of deviation from the true distribution.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1/2$
\end_inset

 represents the point in time at which the marginal distributions of these
 bridges have the most freedom to deviate from the true distribution (in
 contrast, the marginal distribution of the sampled bridges, whether approximate
 or exact, are the same as the unconstrained process at times 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}=\{0,1\}$
\end_inset

 by definition).
 The K-S statistics presented here are therefore an overly stringent view
 of the utility of the approximate sample paths in the MCEM algorithm proposed
 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "chap:EM"

\end_inset

.
 In particular, the proposed MCEM algorithm depends on an integral over
 an entire generalized bridge path, and not only on the value of a bridge
 at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1/2$
\end_inset

.
 In the next section, we will demonstrate that an MCEM algorithm using the
 approximate bridge sampler produces comparable results to one using the
 exact bridge sampler, and demonstrate the correctness of the proposed MCEM
 algorithm more generally.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Simulation-Based Inference on Distributional Data
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Having verified our ability to sample 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

-bridges, we verify in this section the correctness of the MCEM algorithm
 proposed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "chap:EM"

\end_inset

.
 We show that the MCEM scheme converges to the Kullback-Liebler divergence
 minimizing parameter in a variety of settings, often very quickly.
 Furthermore, we demonstrate that using an approximate generalized bridge
 sampler does not seem to adversely affect convergence up to Monte Carlo
 variation.
 Given that the approximate sampler is one to two orders of magnitude faster
 than the exact sampler (as seen in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "tab:KS-stats"

\end_inset

), this is a welcome finding that dramatically increases the utility of
 the proposed MCEM scheme in inference applications.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The theoretical setting for this section is as follows: Suppose we have
 a true but unknown probability model 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset

 admitting a canonical process 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 on the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 Further suppose we wish to model 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 under a family of alternative probability models 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Q}=\{\mathbb{Q}_{\theta}\mid\theta\in\Theta\}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset

 is absolutely continuous to any element of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Q}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{0}=x_{0}$
\end_inset

 is fixed in either model, and we let 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{\mathbb{P}}$
\end_inset

 be the known law of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 under 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset

 at times 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}=\{t_{1},\dots,t_{n}\}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1}>0$
\end_inset

 and we choose 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq2$
\end_inset

 for identifiability reasons.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we will focus on the family of models 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Q}$
\end_inset

 under which 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a Gaussian OU process.
 This is due to the prevalence of such processes as discussed above and
 the analytical tractability of the K-L divergence of their finite-dimensional
 distributions from those of other Gaussian processes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our simulation strategy rests on the following observation: If we can simulate
 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 under 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset

 on the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

, we can take its values at 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}$
\end_inset

 as samples from 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{\mathbb{P}}$
\end_inset

; then, the proposed MCEM scheme given 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{\mathbb{P}}$
\end_inset

 should converge to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 which minimizes the K-L divergence of the law of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 under 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}_{\theta}$
\end_inset

 from its law under 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is an OU diffusion with parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta^{*}$
\end_inset

 under 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset

