\begin_layout Standard
As a first illustrative example, we choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is an OU diffusion governed by the parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta^{*}=(0,1,1)$
\end_inset

 under 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset

.
 The expectation-maximization iterations of a single replication of the
 proposed MCEM algorithm given 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{\mathbb{P}}$
\end_inset

 are presented in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "tab:mcem-stationary"

\end_inset

.
 As noted above, we expect the MCEM estimates to converge to 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Since the OU diffusion has a constant diffusion coefficient, the corresponding
 Lamperti transform is 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{\theta}(x)=x/\theta$
\end_inset

, and the requisite functions for MCEM are readily available from the results
 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "chap:EM"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We qualitatively note from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "tab:mcem-stationary"

\end_inset

 that the exact and approximate MCEM schemes converge quite quickly, with
 no obvious difference between the schemes up to Monte Carlo variation.
 As is usual for MCEM, the algorithm produces parameter estimates sampled
 from some neighborhood of the true parameter value as described in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
before "Section 3.1 in"
key "wei-tanner-1990"

\end_inset

, instead of converging deterministically to such a value.
 Though we expected the slightly thinner tails of the sample paths drawn
 in approximate MCEM to result in some deterioration of the quality of the
 Monte Carlo estimates, the Monte Carlo variation in this experiment renders
 any bias undetectable to the eye.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With a heuristic sense of the dynamics of the MCEM algorithm's convergence,
 we present a comprehensive evaluation of the ability of the proposed algorithm
 to estimate the parameters governing a Gaussian OU diffusion given a variety
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "tab:diff-diffusions"

\end_inset

.
 In particular, we consider true probability models 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset

 under which 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout aEnumerate (ClassicThesis)
an OU diffusion governed by 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta^{*}$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout aEnumerate (ClassicThesis)
a standard Wiener process, and 
\end_layout

\begin_layout aEnumerate (ClassicThesis)
a fractional Wiener process with Hurst parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $H=0.2$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is an OU diffusion under 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset

, as noted above, the MCEM algorithm should simply converge to 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta^{*}$
\end_inset

 since the family of probability models 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Q}$
\end_inset

 is correctly specified.
 In the latter two cases, model misspecification means that the MCEM algorithm
 can only minimize the K-L divergence of the law of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{\mathcal{T}}$
\end_inset

 under 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}_{\theta}$
\end_inset

 from its law under 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset

 to some non-zero quantity.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a Wiener process under 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset

, the K-L divergence is minimized as 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\rightarrow0,\sigma\rightarrow1$
\end_inset

, since the OU diffusion reduces to a Wiener process in such a limit (note
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 in this case is not well-defined).
 Finally, when 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a fractional Wiener process with Hurst parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 under 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset

, the K-L divergence of the law of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1/2,1}$
\end_inset

 under 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}_{\theta}$
\end_inset

 from its law under 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset

 can be found to be
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{2}\left[\mbox{Tr}\left(\Sigma_{O}(\theta)^{-1}\Sigma_{F}(H)\right)+\log\frac{\det\Sigma_{O}(\theta)}{\det\Sigma_{F}(H)}-2\right],
\]

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Sigma_{O}(\theta)=\frac{\sigma^{2}}{2\lambda}\begin{bmatrix}1-e^{-\lambda} & e^{-\lambda/2}-e^{-3\lambda/2}\\
e^{-\lambda/2}-e^{-3\lambda/2} & 1-e^{-2\lambda}
\end{bmatrix},\Sigma_{F}(H)=\begin{bmatrix}2^{-2H} & 1/2\\
1/2 & 1
\end{bmatrix}
\]

\end_inset

are the covariance matrices of the values of an OU diffusion and a fractional
 Wiener process with Hurst parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 at times 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}=\{1/2,1\}$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 We choose 
\begin_inset Formula $H=0.2$
\end_inset

 so that the fractional Wiener process that mean reverts (preventing 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 from binding at 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

), and numerically find the K-L divergence minimizing parameter to be approximat
ely 
\begin_inset Formula $(0.00,0.83,1.45)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

