 for the Wiener process is in some cases quite large; this is a result of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 not being well-defined when 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=0$
\end_inset

.
 The Wiener process is also the only process for which the mean MKLDE is
 greater than a standard deviation away from the true parameter value; this
 is because the parameter space of an OU process is restricted to 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda>0$
\end_inset

, so estimates for 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=0$
\end_inset

 will inevitably be biased positively.
 It is not clear to us why the estimates for 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 across all experiments seem to be much more variable than the estimates
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

.
 We conjecture that this is a result of continuous diffusion paths over
 a compact interval containing infinite information about 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

, while only containing finite information about the drift parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "nielsen-shephard-2002"

\end_inset

); perhaps in the case of an OU process, it is 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 in particular for which information is sparse.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Furthermore, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "tab:diff-diffusions"

\end_inset

 demonstrates the robustness of the proposed MCEM scheme to various assumptions.
 We note that the finite sample experiments using 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\nu}_{\mathbb{P}}$
\end_inset

 as a plug-in estimator for 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{\mathbb{P}}$
\end_inset

 display lower efficiency but remain accurate despite the violation of technical
 conditions on the absolute continuity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\nu}_{\mathbb{P}}$
\end_inset

 with respect to the elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Q}$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, the biased estimates we expected under approximate MCEM do
 not appear up to Monte Carlo variation; we hypothesize that this is due
 to the approximate sample paths being of high quality over a sufficiently
 high proportion of the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the unbiased estimates of approximate MCEM in mind, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "tab:diff-diffusions"

\end_inset

 also shows that the exact MCEM scheme also does not appear to have obviously
 less variability than the approximate scheme.
 In addition, as seen in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "tab:KS-stats"

\end_inset

, the computational time taken by an exact MCEM scheme is at least an order
 of a magnitude greater than the time needed for approximate MCEM, which
 itself is already non-trivial (on the order of five hours for the experiments
 shown here, mostly due to the numerous evaluations of the objective function
 needed for stochastic optimization).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We hypothesize that for all but the most extreme of distributional data
 (i.e.
 conditioning a process displaying strong mean reversion on marginal distributio
ns centered far from the mean), approximate MCEM will provide parameter
 estimates of sufficiently high quality for practical purposes.
 In particular, we hold that using approximate sample paths offers vast
 computational gains vis-à-vis exact paths, and results in bias which is
 most likely small relative to the variance resulting from Monte Carlo estimates
 and stochastic optimization methods.
 
\end_layout

